<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="aa-section-earth-subsection-i" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Expanding the total derivative of <m>\hat{i}</m></title>

  <p>
    There are only two differences between the derivation of <m>\dfrac{D \hat{i}}{Dt}</m> for a disk at latitude <m>\phi</m> on Earth
    and the derivation of <m>\dfrac{D \hat{i}}{Dt}</m> for the turntable.
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>\vec{\delta i}</m> points in the direction of <m>\hat{j} \, \sin{\phi} - \hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}</m>
                rather than in the direction of <m>\hat{j}</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>R = a \cos{\phi}</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    Therefore,
  </p>

  <p>
    <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-i-final-earth" number="yes"> 
        \frac{D \hat{i}}{D t}
        =
        \Omega \left(
        \hat{j} \sin{\phi}
        - \hat{k} \cos{\phi}
        \right)
        =
        \Omega \sin{\phi} \, \hat{j}
        - \Omega \cos{\phi} \, \hat{k}
    </md>
  </p>

</subsection>